[4] China CDC Weekly Report: Epidemiology of COVID-19 outbreak, China
Date: Mon 17 Feb 2020
Source: China CDC Weekly Report 17 Feb 2020 [edited]
http://weekly.chinacdc.cn/en/article/id/e53946e2-c6c4-41e9-9a9b-fea8db1a8f51


Corresponding Author: Yanping Zhang <zhangyp@chinacdc.cn>
The epidemiological characteristics of an outbreak of 2019 novel coronavirus disease (COVID-19) -- China, 2020
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
Background
An outbreak of 2019 novel coronavirus diseases (COVID-19) in Wuhan, Hubei Province China has spread quickly nationwide. Here, we report results of a descriptive, explanatory analysis of all cases diagnosed as of [11 Feb 2020].

Methods
All COVID-19 cases reported through [11 Feb 2020] were extracted from China's Infectious Disease Information System.
Analyses included the following:
1. summary of patient characteristics;
2. examination of age distributions and sex ratios;
3. calculation of case fatality and mortality rates;
4. geo-temporal analysis of viral spread;
5. epidemiological curve construction; and 6. subgroup analysis.

Results
A total of 72 314 patient records -- 44 672 (61.8%) confirmed cases, 16 186 (22.4%) suspected cases, 10 567 (14.6%) clinically diagnosed cases (Hubei Province only), and 889 asymptomatic cases (1.2%) -- contributed data for the analysis.

Among confirmed cases, most were aged 30-79 years (86.6%), diagnosed in Hubei (74.7%) and considered mild (80.9%). diagnosed in Hubei (74.7%), and considered mild (80.9%). A total of 1023 deaths occurred among confirmed cases for an overall case fatality rate of 2.3%. The COVID-19 spread outward from Hubei Province sometime after December 2019, and by [11 Feb 2020], 1386 counties across all 31 provinces were affected. The epidemic curve of onset of symptoms peaked around [23-26 Jan 2020], then began to decline leading up to 11 Feb 2020. A total of 1716 health workers have become infected and 5 have died (0.3%).

Conclusions
COVID-19 epidemic has spread very quickly taking only 30 days to expand from Hubei to the rest of Mainland China. With many people returning from a long holiday, China needs to prepare for the possible rebound of the epidemic.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This is the 1st large study of all confirmed cases of COVID-2 reported to the Chinese National Health Information System as of 11 Feb 2020.

Additional details in the method section that clarifies the presentation of results are noteworthy. In classifying clinical presentation, the authors defined cases as mild, severe, or critical. Mild were those whose clinical course was either non-pneumonia or a mild pneumonia. Severe included those who had dyspnea (shortness of breath), respiratory rate greater than or equal to 30 per minute, a blood oxygen saturation of less than or equal to 93%, and a PaO2/FiO2 ratio (the ratio of arterial oxygen partial pressure to fractional inspired oxygen) of 50% within 24-48 hours. Critical cases were defined as individuals with respiratory failure, septic shock and/or multi-organ dysfunction or failure. Health workers included all individuals working in a healthcare facility, not just doctors and nurses. Of note, the variables Wuhan-related exposure, comorbid condition, and case severity were not mandatory reporting fields, so information was not available on all reported cases.

Date of onset was self-described date of onset of either fever or cough. For asymptomatic cases, the date of positive viral nucleic acid test results was taken as date of onset for purposes of the epidemic curves in the paper. Suspected cases were those who were diagnosed clinically, based on symptoms and exposures, whereas those clinically diagnosed cases were suspected cases with abnormal pulmonary imaging consistent with coronavirus pneumonia.

A sobering set of analyses in the baseline characteristics of the cases was the age specific case fatality rates (CFR). The overall CFR among the 72 000+ cases analyzed was 2.3 %. In the 0-9 years the CFR was 0 as no deaths were reported out of 416 cases; in the 10-19 years, 20-29 years and 30-39 years age groups the CFR was 0.2%. In the 40-49 years, the CFR was 0.4%, the 50-59 years 1.3 %, 60-69 years 3.6 %, 70-79% 8.0% and the 80 years or older 14.8%.

CFRs by type of co-morbidities: cardiovascular disease 10.5%, diabetes 7.3%, chronic respiratory disease 6.3%, hypertension 6.0%, cancer 5.6%, and none 2.6%

An interesting look at the CFRs by time period: Before 31 Dec 2019 14.4%; 1-10 Jan 2020 15.6%; 11-20 Jan 2020 5.7%; 21-31 Jan 2020 1.9%; and after 1 Feb 2020 0.8%. Possibly attributable to the known phenomenon of early recognition of more serious cases, followed by introduction of testing (12 Jan 2020), combined with health services overwhelmed by the volume of cases and the volume of ICU care beds needed.

There is an excellent series on the geo-temporal progression of the outbreak in China available at Figure 2 at the source URL. Figure 3 shows epidemiological curves of the number of cases by date of onset of confirmed cases, compared with suspected cases, clinically diagnosed cases, and asymptomatic cases. Figures 3A and 3B are epidemiological curves by date of onset of confirmed cases compared with number of cases diagnosed each day for confirmed cases.

Figure 4A shows the epidemiological curve for cases reported outside of Hubei, and figure 4B shows the epidemiological curve for cases among healthcare personnel (a total of 3019 if one includes suspected and clinically confirmed cases.)

The author's conclusion is noting the highly infectious nature of this coronavirus with spread from one city to countrywide in approximately 30 days, even with the shutdown and isolation of whole cities, cancellation of New Year celebrations, prohibition of school and work attendance, and rapid construction of hospitals. They note the good news, that the disease is mild for 81% of patients with a low overall CFR of 2.3%

The authors note that there seem to be 2 different transmission patterns of this outbreak. The 1st they describe as a continuous common source pattern of spread in December 2019 and then the 2nd pattern from early January 2020 through 11 Feb 2020 (and presumably onward in time) a propagated source pattern. Consistent with the ongoing theory of possible multiple common source exposures in the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market I Wuhan City, where the virus was transmitted from animal (as yet unknown) to humans, followed by the viruses high mutation and recombination rates to facilitate rapid human-to-human transmission.

The authors raise the following questions still needing addressing: identification of the animal reservoir, determination of infectiousness period, identification of transmission routes, and effective treatment and prevention methods, including further test development, drug development, and vaccine development.

While they note a leveling off of transmission, they caution there may be another increase in transmission as people return to work and school as the isolation measures are lifted. - Mod.MPP]

